{"title_page": "Sam Tarry", "text_new": "{{short description|British Labour politician, MP for Ilford South}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Sam Tarry\n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n| image = Official portrait of Sam Tarry MP crop 2.jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = Tarry in 2019\n| office1 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Ilford South (UK Parliament constituency)|Ilford South]]\n| term_start1 = 12 December 2019\n| term_end1 = \n| majority1 = 24,101 (45.1%)\n| predecessor1 = [[Mike Gapes]]\n| successor1 = \n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = August 1982\n| birth_place = [[Westminster]], England\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| alma_mater = \n| party = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n| website = [https://www.samtarry.org Sam Tarry for Ilford South]\n}}\n'''Samuel Peter Tarry'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hansard.parliament.uk/Commons/2019-12-18/debates/2E37F0BD-4DF0-40A6-B9F9-0607212DBFB1/MembersSworn|publisher=parliament.uk|date=18 December 2019|accessdate=17 January 2020|title=Members Sworn}}</ref> (born August 1982) is a British politician who has been the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Ilford South (UK Parliament constituency)|Ilford South]] since the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 general election]]. A member of the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]], he was the director of [[Jeremy Corbyn]]'s [[2016 Labour Party leadership election (UK)|2016 Labour Party leadership]] campaign and currently serves as a national director of its successor organisation, [[Momentum (organisation)|Momentum]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Swinford|first=Steven|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/08/28/jeremy-corbyn-ally-works-as-councillor-in-london-but-has-marital/|title=Jeremy Corbyn's adviser works as councillor in London but has marital home 70 miles away|date=28 August 2016|work=The Daily Telegraph}}</ref><ref name=\"Gilligan\">{{cite news|last1=Gilligan|first=Andrew|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/double-life-of-corbyn-henchman-mr9xt6s5k|title='Double life' of Corbyn henchman|date=28 August 2016|work=The Sunday Times}}{{subscription required}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nTarry was born in August 1982<ref>{{cite web|url=https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/officers/48ly2_kdHnjXlDCXMifJKhooEwE/appointments|title=Samuel Peter Tarry \u2013 Personal Appointments|publisher=[[Companies House]]|accessdate=8 January 2020}}</ref> in [[Westminster]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?r=269758151:6795&d=bmd_1581352778|title=FreeBMD Entry Info|website=www.freebmd.org.uk|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref> and grew up on an estate in [[Dagenham]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://liberalconspiracy.org/2009/02/26/why-im-standing-for-young-labour-chair/|title=Why I'm standing for Young Labour chair {{!}} Liberal Conspiracy|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref>\n\nHe has commented that he attended [[Highlands Primary School, Redbridge]] and that his first job was as a cleaner at [[Redbridge College]].<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.ilfordrecorder.co.uk/news/crime-court/ilford-born-sam-tarry-running-to-be-labour-s-next-ilford-south-candidate-1-6223695|title=Trade union official Sam Tarry hoping to be named Labour's next parliamentary candidate for Ilford South|journal=Ilford Recorder|first=Matthew|last=Clemenson|date=24 August 2019|access-date=21 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe is a previous chairman of [[Young Labour (UK)|Young Labour]] and was also a community organiser for advocacy group [[Hope not Hate]] in [[Dagenham]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newstatesman.com/blogs/dan-hodges/2011/01/young-labour-campaign-quigley|last=Hodges|first=Dan|title=Young Labour leaked email|date=28 January 2011|work=New Statesman}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://labourlist.org/2010/07/organising-for-labour-organising-to-win/|publisher=LabourList|title=Organising for Labour. Organising to win|last=Tarry|first=Sam|date=16 July 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/profile/sam-tarry|work=The Guardian|title=Sam Tarry|accessdate=17 January 2020}}</ref> Tarry served as the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] councillor for Chadwell Heath ward on the [[Barking and Dagenham London Borough Council]] from 2010 to 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://modgov.lbbd.gov.uk/internet/mgUserInfo.aspx?UID=1746&RPID=0|publisher=Barking and Dagenham London Borough Council|title=Cllr Sam Tarry|accessdate=17 January 2020}}</ref> \n\nPrior to his election to Parliament, Tarry was the national political officer for the [[Transport Salaried Staffs' Association|TSSA]] trade union, and the president of the left-wing think tank, Centre for Labour and Social Studies (CLASS).<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=https://labourlist.org/2019/10/sam-tarry-wins-ilford-south-selection-to-replace-mike-gapes/|title=Sam Tarry wins Ilford South selection to replace Mike Gapes|last=Rodgers|first=Sienna|date=22 October 2019|publisher=LabourList}}</ref>\n\n==Parliamentary career==\nTarry was selected as the Labour candidate for [[Ilford South (UK Parliament constituency)|Ilford South]] on 22 October 2019. His selection as the Labour candidate for Ilford South was controversial, as the day before members were due to vote, local Redbridge Council leader [[Jas Athwal]], considered the frontrunner in the contest, was suspended from the party.<ref name=Pogrund>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-49944605|title=Redbridge Council leader suspended over 'serious allegation'|publisher=BBC News|date=5 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/corbyn-friends-stitch-up-seats-63jqqm69c|title=Corbyn friends 'stitch up' seats|work=The Sunday Times|date=20 October 2019|last1=Pogrund|first1=Gabriel|last2=Wheeler|first2=Caroline}}{{subscription required}}</ref> Tarry was subsequently selected in a vote a few weeks later with Athwal excluded from the ballot.<ref name=\":2\" /> \n\nHe was elected as Ilford South MP in the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 general election]] with a majority of 24,101 (45.1%). The constituency was previously represented by [[Mike Gapes]] who left Labour to join [[Change UK]] in February 2019.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=BBC News|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000760|title=Ilford South|accessdate=17 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter being elected to Parliament, Tarry was appointed to the [[Transport Select Committee]], on which he has been credited as being a \"passionate advocate for public ownership\" <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tssa.org.uk/en/whats-new/news/index.cfm/tssa-welcomes-appointment-of-passionate-advocate-for-public-ownership-sam-tarry-to-transport-select-committee|title=TSSA welcomes appointment of \"passionate advocate for public ownership\" Sam Tarry to Transport Select Committee - News|website=www.tssa.org.uk|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> \n\nHe also joined the [[Socialist Campaign Group]] of left-wing Labour MPs.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Correspondent|first=Esther Webber, Red Box Reporter {{!}} Oliver Wright, Policy Editor {{!}} Henry Zeffman, Political|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/labour-leadership-corbynistas-oppose-angela-rayners-bid-to-be-deputy-rwdlzzz95|title=Labour leadership: Corbynistas oppose Angela Rayner\u2019s bid to be deputy|access-date=2020-04-11|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref> He has used his position in Parliament to advocate for the Labour party to appeal to working class and northern communities, claiming in the [[2020 Labour Party leadership election|2020 Labour leadership election]] that [[Keir Starmer]] would be unsuited to the role of Leader, because of his \"North London lawyer\" image.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.guardian-series.co.uk/news/18145495.sam-tarry-questions-keir-starmers-north-london-lawyer-image/|title=Ilford South MP questions Keir Starmer's 'north London lawyer' image|website=East London and West Essex Guardian Series|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> Tarry subsequently endorsed [[Rebecca Long-Bailey]] in the contest.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://labourlist.org/2020/01/rolling-list-mp-mep-nominations-for-labour-leadership-candidates/|title=Rolling list: MP/MEP nominations for Labour leadership candidates|date=2020-01-08|website=LabourList|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\n== Controversy ==\nDuring the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 general election]], Tarry sparked controversy for claiming that \"people associated with the Labour Party have sought to exploit the issue [of antisemitism] just because they don\u2019t agree with Jeremy Corbyn over an issue of foreign policy.\", which was thought to allude to antisemitism claims in Labour being made maliciously by those who disagreed with Corbyn's foreign policy position on Israel.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|last=Phillips|first=Alek|url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/ilford-south-labour-candidate-says-labour-associates-exploit-antisemitism-because-they-disagree-wi-1.493664|title=Ilford South Labour candidate says people in the party 'exploit' antisemitism to attack Corbyn 'over foreign policy'|date=28 November 2019|work=The Jewish Chronicle}}</ref> \n\nThe [[Jewish Labour Movement]] labelled his comments \"a tired old trope that the EHRC inquiry is motivated by a desire to smear Corbyn\" and considered Tarry's comments \"beyond disappointing\"<ref name=\":0\" /> Tarry rebutted allegations that his comments were antisemitic or sought to downplay it, stating that antisemitism \"is something I care deeply about and would never seek to downplay.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jewishnews.timesofisrael.com/labour-candidate-claims-some-exploit-antisemitism-over-foreign-policy-clash/|title=Labour candidate claims some \u2018exploit\u2019 antisemitism over foreign policy clash|last=Frot|first=Mathilde|website=jewishnews.timesofisrael.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020, Tarry faced renewed criticism over his stance on antisemitism, after he refused to condemn a motion, widely reported as antisemitic, passed at a branch of the Labour Party in Ilford South.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://antisemitism.uk/scandal-erupts-at-pro-corbyn-mp-sam-tarrys-local-branch-where-senior-jvl-members-who-originally-nominated-him-as-labour-candidate-submit-an-antisemitic-motion-which-he-fails-to-condemn/|title=Scandal erupts at pro-Corbyn MP Sam Tarry\u2019s local branch, where senior JVL members who originally nominated him as Labour candidate submit an antisemitic motion which he fails to condemn|last=Jonathan|date=2020-01-21|website=Campaign Against Antisemitism|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> The motion about the [[Board of Deputies of British Jews]], the largest Jewish communal organisation in the UK, accused it of being \"consistent in its support for the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]]\".<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/labour-mp-faces-mounting-criticism-for-not-condemning-motion-1.495443|title= Labour MP faces mounting criticism for not condemning motion attacking Board of Deputies|work=[[The Jewish Chronicle]]|author= Harpin, Lee|date = 15 January 2020|access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref> At the meeting, members against the motion were reportedly called \"agents of a foreign power\" among other antisemitic tropes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.algemeiner.com/2020/01/14/uk-labour-party-member-allegedly-called-foreign-agent-for-opposing-motion-attacking-jewish-advocacy-group/|title=UK Labour Party Member Allegedly Called \u2018Foreign Agent\u2019 for Opposing Motion Attacking Jewish Advocacy Group|website=Algemeiner.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> Tarry responded by claiming that \"there are conflicting accounts of what happened and what was said\".<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Personal life==\nTarry is married to [[pediatrics|paediatrician]] Dr. Julia Fozard who works in Brighton.<ref name=Gilligan/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/aug/28/corbyn-adviser-sam-tarry-denies-claims-electoral-fraud-barking-address|work=The Guardian|title=Corbyn adviser denies claims of electoral fraud over registered address|date=28 August 2016|accessdate=17 January 2020|last=Lyons|first=Kate}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*{{Official website}}\n*{{UK MP links |parliament=4829 |publicwhip=Sam_Tarry |theywork=25912}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Mike Gapes]]}}\n{{s-ttl\n |title =[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Ilford South (UK Parliament constituency)|Ilford South]]\n |years=[[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019]]\u2013present\n}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{London Labour Party MPs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tarry, Sam}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:Councillors in the London Borough of Barking and Dagenham]]\n[[Category:English anti-fascists]]\n[[Category:English anti\u2013Iraq War activists]]\n[[Category:English socialists]]\n[[Category:English trade unionists]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) councillors]]\n[[Category:People from Dagenham]]\n[[Category:People from Ilford]]\n[[Category:People from Westminster]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2019\u2013]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British Labour politician, MP for Ilford South}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Sam Tarry\n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n| image = Official portrait of Sam Tarry MP crop 2.jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = Tarry in 2019\n| office1 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Ilford South (UK Parliament constituency)|Ilford South]]\n| term_start1 = 12 December 2019\n| term_end1 = \n| majority1 = 24,101 (45.1%)\n| predecessor1 = [[Mike Gapes]]\n| successor1 = \n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = August 1982\n| birth_place = [[Westminster]], England\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| alma_mater = \n| party = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n| website = [https://www.samtarry.org Sam Tarry for Ilford South]\n}}\n'''Samuel Peter Tarry'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hansard.parliament.uk/Commons/2019-12-18/debates/2E37F0BD-4DF0-40A6-B9F9-0607212DBFB1/MembersSworn|publisher=parliament.uk|date=18 December 2019|accessdate=17 January 2020|title=Members Sworn}}</ref> (born August 1982) is a British politician who has been the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Ilford South (UK Parliament constituency)|Ilford South]] since the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 general election]]. A member of the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]], he was the director of [[Jeremy Corbyn]]'s [[2016 Labour Party leadership election (UK)|2016 Labour Party leadership]] campaign and currently serves as a national director of its successor organisation, [[Momentum (organisation)|Momentum]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Swinford|first=Steven|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/08/28/jeremy-corbyn-ally-works-as-councillor-in-london-but-has-marital/|title=Jeremy Corbyn's adviser works as councillor in London but has marital home 70 miles away|date=28 August 2016|work=The Daily Telegraph}}</ref><ref name=\"Gilligan\">{{cite news|last1=Gilligan|first=Andrew|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/double-life-of-corbyn-henchman-mr9xt6s5k|title='Double life' of Corbyn henchman|date=28 August 2016|work=The Sunday Times}}{{subscription required}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nTarry was born in August 1982<ref>{{cite web|url=https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/officers/48ly2_kdHnjXlDCXMifJKhooEwE/appointments|title=Samuel Peter Tarry \u2013 Personal Appointments|publisher=[[Companies House]]|accessdate=8 January 2020}}</ref> in [[Westminster]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?r=269758151:6795&d=bmd_1581352778|title=FreeBMD Entry Info|website=www.freebmd.org.uk|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref> and grew up on an estate in [[Dagenham]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://liberalconspiracy.org/2009/02/26/why-im-standing-for-young-labour-chair/|title=Why I'm standing for Young Labour chair {{!}} Liberal Conspiracy|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref>\n\nHe has commented that he attended [[Highlands Primary School, Redbridge]] and that his first job was as a cleaner at [[Redbridge College]].<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.ilfordrecorder.co.uk/news/crime-court/ilford-born-sam-tarry-running-to-be-labour-s-next-ilford-south-candidate-1-6223695|title=Trade union official Sam Tarry hoping to be named Labour's next parliamentary candidate for Ilford South|journal=Ilford Recorder|first=Matthew|last=Clemenson|date=24 August 2019|access-date=21 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe is a previous chairman of [[Young Labour (UK)|Young Labour]] and was also a community organiser for advocacy group [[Hope not Hate]] in [[Dagenham]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newstatesman.com/blogs/dan-hodges/2011/01/young-labour-campaign-quigley|last=Hodges|first=Dan|title=Young Labour leaked email|date=28 January 2011|work=New Statesman}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://labourlist.org/2010/07/organising-for-labour-organising-to-win/|publisher=LabourList|title=Organising for Labour. Organising to win|last=Tarry|first=Sam|date=16 July 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/profile/sam-tarry|work=The Guardian|title=Sam Tarry|accessdate=17 January 2020}}</ref> Tarry served as the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] councillor for Chadwell Heath ward on the [[Barking and Dagenham London Borough Council]] from 2010 to 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://modgov.lbbd.gov.uk/internet/mgUserInfo.aspx?UID=1746&RPID=0|publisher=Barking and Dagenham London Borough Council|title=Cllr Sam Tarry|accessdate=17 January 2020}}</ref> \n\nPrior to his election to Parliament, Tarry was the national political officer for the [[Transport Salaried Staffs' Association|TSSA]] trade union, and the president of the left-wing think tank, Centre for Labour and Social Studies (CLASS).<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=https://labourlist.org/2019/10/sam-tarry-wins-ilford-south-selection-to-replace-mike-gapes/|title=Sam Tarry wins Ilford South selection to replace Mike Gapes|last=Rodgers|first=Sienna|date=22 October 2019|publisher=LabourList}}</ref>\n\n==Parliamentary career==\nTarry was selected as the Labour candidate for [[Ilford South (UK Parliament constituency)|Ilford South]] on 22 October 2019. His selection as the Labour candidate for Ilford South was controversial, as the day before members were due to vote, local Redbridge Council leader [[Jas Athwal]], considered the frontrunner in the contest, was suspended from the party over an unspecified \"serious allegation\".<ref name=Pogrund>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-49944605|title=Redbridge Council leader suspended over 'serious allegation'|publisher=BBC News|date=5 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/corbyn-friends-stitch-up-seats-63jqqm69c|title=Corbyn friends 'stitch up' seats|work=The Sunday Times|date=20 October 2019|last1=Pogrund|first1=Gabriel|last2=Wheeler|first2=Caroline}}{{subscription required}}</ref> Tarry was subsequently selected in a vote a few weeks later with Athwal excluded from the ballot.<ref name=\":2\" /> \n\nHe was elected as Ilford South MP in the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 general election]] with a majority of 24,101 (45.1%). The constituency was previously represented by [[Mike Gapes]] who left Labour to join [[Change UK]] in February 2019.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=BBC News|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000760|title=Ilford South|accessdate=17 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter being elected to Parliament, Tarry was appointed to the [[Transport Select Committee]], on which he has been credited as being a \"passionate advocate for public ownership\" <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tssa.org.uk/en/whats-new/news/index.cfm/tssa-welcomes-appointment-of-passionate-advocate-for-public-ownership-sam-tarry-to-transport-select-committee|title=TSSA welcomes appointment of \"passionate advocate for public ownership\" Sam Tarry to Transport Select Committee - News|website=www.tssa.org.uk|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> \n\nHe also joined the [[Socialist Campaign Group]] of left-wing Labour MPs.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Correspondent|first=Esther Webber, Red Box Reporter {{!}} Oliver Wright, Policy Editor {{!}} Henry Zeffman, Political|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/labour-leadership-corbynistas-oppose-angela-rayners-bid-to-be-deputy-rwdlzzz95|title=Labour leadership: Corbynistas oppose Angela Rayner\u2019s bid to be deputy|access-date=2020-04-11|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref> He has used his position in Parliament to advocate for the Labour party to appeal to working class and northern communities, claiming in the [[2020 Labour Party leadership election|2020 Labour leadership election]] that [[Keir Starmer]] would be unsuited to the role of Leader, because of his \"North London lawyer\" image.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.guardian-series.co.uk/news/18145495.sam-tarry-questions-keir-starmers-north-london-lawyer-image/|title=Ilford South MP questions Keir Starmer's 'north London lawyer' image|website=East London and West Essex Guardian Series|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> Tarry subsequently endorsed [[Rebecca Long-Bailey]] in the contest.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://labourlist.org/2020/01/rolling-list-mp-mep-nominations-for-labour-leadership-candidates/|title=Rolling list: MP/MEP nominations for Labour leadership candidates|date=2020-01-08|website=LabourList|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\n== Controversy ==\nDuring the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 general election]], Tarry sparked controversy for claiming that \"people associated with the Labour Party have sought to exploit the issue [of antisemitism] just because they don\u2019t agree with Jeremy Corbyn over an issue of foreign policy.\", which was thought to allude to antisemitism claims in Labour being made maliciously by those who disagreed with Corbyn's foreign policy position on Israel.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|last=Phillips|first=Alek|url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/ilford-south-labour-candidate-says-labour-associates-exploit-antisemitism-because-they-disagree-wi-1.493664|title=Ilford South Labour candidate says people in the party 'exploit' antisemitism to attack Corbyn 'over foreign policy'|date=28 November 2019|work=The Jewish Chronicle}}</ref> The [[Jewish Labour Movement]] labelled his comments \"a tired old trope that the EHRC inquiry is motivated by a desire to smear Corbyn\" and considered Tarry's comments \"beyond disappointing\"<ref name=\":0\" /> Tarry rebutted allegations that his comments were antisemitic or sought to downplay it, replying that \"many of my friends were Jewish people\" and that antisemitism \"is something I care deeply about and would never seek to downplay.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jewishnews.timesofisrael.com/labour-candidate-claims-some-exploit-antisemitism-over-foreign-policy-clash/|title=Labour candidate claims some \u2018exploit\u2019 antisemitism over foreign policy clash|last=Frot|first=Mathilde|website=jewishnews.timesofisrael.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020, Tarry faced renewed criticism over his stance on antisemitism, after he refused to condemn a motion, widely reported as antisemitic, passed at a branch of the Labour Party in Ilford South.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://antisemitism.uk/scandal-erupts-at-pro-corbyn-mp-sam-tarrys-local-branch-where-senior-jvl-members-who-originally-nominated-him-as-labour-candidate-submit-an-antisemitic-motion-which-he-fails-to-condemn/|title=Scandal erupts at pro-Corbyn MP Sam Tarry\u2019s local branch, where senior JVL members who originally nominated him as Labour candidate submit an antisemitic motion which he fails to condemn|last=Jonathan|date=2020-01-21|website=Campaign Against Antisemitism|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> The motion about the [[Board of Deputies of British Jews]], the largest Jewish communal organisation in the UK, accused it of being \"consistent in its support for the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]]\".<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/labour-mp-faces-mounting-criticism-for-not-condemning-motion-1.495443|title= Labour MP faces mounting criticism for not condemning motion attacking Board of Deputies|work=[[The Jewish Chronicle]]|author= Harpin, Lee|date = 15 January 2020|access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref> At the meeting, members against the motion were reportedly called \"agents of a foreign power\" among other antisemitic tropes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.algemeiner.com/2020/01/14/uk-labour-party-member-allegedly-called-foreign-agent-for-opposing-motion-attacking-jewish-advocacy-group/|title=UK Labour Party Member Allegedly Called \u2018Foreign Agent\u2019 for Opposing Motion Attacking Jewish Advocacy Group|website=Algemeiner.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> Tarry responded by claiming that \"there are conflicting accounts of what happened and what was said\".<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Personal life==\nTarry is married to [[pediatrics|paediatrician]] Dr. Julia Fozard who works in Brighton.<ref name=Gilligan/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/aug/28/corbyn-adviser-sam-tarry-denies-claims-electoral-fraud-barking-address|work=The Guardian|title=Corbyn adviser denies claims of electoral fraud over registered address|date=28 August 2016|accessdate=17 January 2020|last=Lyons|first=Kate}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*{{Official website}}\n*{{UK MP links |parliament=4829 |publicwhip=Sam_Tarry |theywork=25912}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Mike Gapes]]}}\n{{s-ttl\n |title =[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Ilford South (UK Parliament constituency)|Ilford South]]\n |years=[[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019]]\u2013present\n}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{London Labour Party MPs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tarry, Sam}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:Councillors in the London Borough of Barking and Dagenham]]\n[[Category:English anti-fascists]]\n[[Category:English anti\u2013Iraq War activists]]\n[[Category:English socialists]]\n[[Category:English trade unionists]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) councillors]]\n[[Category:People from Dagenham]]\n[[Category:People from Ilford]]\n[[Category:People from Westminster]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2019\u2013]]\n", "name_user": "Hasan8888", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sam_Tarry"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in West Virginia", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing pandemic in West Virginia, United States}}\n{{Current event|2=current pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in West Virginia\n| width           = \n| image           = West Virginia National Guard (49667643407).jpg\n| image_size      = \n| image_upright   = \n| alt             = \n| caption         = Members of the [[West Virginia National Guard]] provide personal protective equipment training on March 16, 2020\n| map1            = COVID-19 In West Virginia County Map.svg\n| legend1         = Density of COVID-19 cases in West Virginia as of April 10\n{{legend|#FFE4A3|1\u201319 cases}}{{legend|#F2A88D|20\u201399 cases}}\n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| map4            = \n| legend4         = \n| map5            = \n| legend5         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[West Virginia]], U.S.\n| first_case      = [[Shepherdstown, West Virginia|Shepherdstown]]\n| arrival_date    = March 17, 2020\n| date            = \n| origin          = \n| confirmed_cases = 574<ref name=\"WVDHHS\">{{cite web |title=Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19) |url=https://dhhr.wv.gov/COVID-19/Pages/default.aspx |publisher=West Virginia Department of Health and Human Services |accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"COVID-19 Daily Update - 4-9-2020 5PM\">{{cite web |title=COVID-19 Daily Update - 4-9-2020 5PM|url=https://dhhr.wv.gov/News/2020/Pages/COVID-19-Daily-Update---4-9-2020---5-PM.aspx |website=dhhr.wv.gov |publisher=[[Government of West Virginia]] |accessdate=April 10, 2020 |date=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n| suspected_cases = \n| severe_cases    = 30<ref name=\"WVDHHS\"/>\n| recovery_cases  = 63<ref name=\"WVDHHS\"/>\n| deaths          = 5<ref name=\"WVDHHS\"/>\n| territories     = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{URL|https://dhhr.wv.gov/COVID-19}}\n}}\n\nThe U.S. state of [[West Virginia]] reported its first case of [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] on March 17, 2020, becoming the last state in the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|United States]] to do so.<ref name=cbspittsburgh>{{cite web|url=https://pittsburgh.cbslocal.com/2020/03/17/coronavirus-in-west-virginia-state-reports-first-positive-covid-19-case/ |title=Coronavirus In West Virginia: State Reports First Positive COVID-19 Case|publisher=CBS Pittsburgh|date=March 17, 2020|accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref> On April 1, 2020 the state reported its first COVID-19 death.<ref name=\"WVDHHS\"/> As of April 10, 2020 the state had reported 574 cases and 5 deaths.<ref name=\"WVDHHS\"/>\n\n==Timeline==\nAs of March 16, the state had tested 84 suspected cases.<ref name=\":22\">{{Cite news|last=Wines|first=Michael|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/14/us/weve-got-a-monster-thats-looming-west-virginia-is-the-last-state-without-a-coronavirus-case.html|title='We've Got a Monster That's Looming': West Virginia Is the Last State Without a Coronavirus Case|date=2020-03-14|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-17|last2=Robertson|first2=Campbell|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> West Virginia announced its first case, in [[Shepherdstown, West Virginia|Shepherdstown]], on March 17, 2020.<ref name=\"wowktv\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wowktv.com/news/west-virginia/covid-19-confirmed-in-west-virginia/|title=COVID-19 confirmed in West Virginia|date=March 17, 2020|website=WOWK 13 News|language=en-US|access-date=March 17, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"wsaz\" /><ref>{{cite news|last=McGuire|first=Colin|date=March 18, 2020|title=First confirmed WV Coronavirus case in Shepherdstown, wife to get tested|url=https://www.journal-news.net/journal-news/first-confirmed-wv-coronavirus-case-in-shepherdstown-wife-to-get/article_3033c813-4675-58a1-b127-d91fc97e1178.html|newspaper=The Journal|location=Martinsburg, West Virginia|access-date=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs of March 18, the second case was announced. Also on that date, 148 West Virginians had been tested for the virus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wvmetronews.com/2020/03/18/second-coronavirus-case-in-west-virginia-confirmed/|title=2nd coronavirus case in West Virginia confirmed|last=WVMetroNews|date=2020-03-19|website=WV MetroNews|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n\nAs of March 20, West Virginia had confirmed 8 cases of COVID-19.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wvmetronews.com/2020/03/20/eighth-coronavirus-case-confirmed-first-case-recognized-in-kanawha-county/|title=Eighth coronavirus case confirmed; first case recognized in Kanawha County|last=WVMetroNews|date=2020-03-20|website=WV MetroNews|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref> On March 22, there were 16 confirmed cases.<ref name=\"WVDHHS\"/>\n\nA March 22 [[The Washington Post|Washington Post]] article described efforts to implement [[social distancing]] in [[Grant County, West Virginia|Grant County]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Frankel |first1=Todd |title=In pro-Trump West Virginia, a fight to convince residents a pandemic is coming |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/2020/03/22/pro-trump-west-virginia-fight-convince-residents-pandemic-is-coming/ |work=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |date=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Government responses==\nOn March 13, Governor [[Jim Justice]] announced all schools across the state would close beginning on March 16, 2020 for an indefinite period of time as a proactive measure.<ref name=wsaz2>{{Cite web |url=https://www.wsaz.com/content/news/WVa-Governor-closing-state-schools-indefinitely-568772291.html |title=W.Va. Gov. Justice closing state schools indefinitely |last=Tierney |first=Brendan |date=March 13, 2020 |website=[[WSAZ-TV]] |language=english |access-date=March 15, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314093424/https://www.wsaz.com/content/news/WVa-Governor-closing-state-schools-indefinitely-568772291.html |archive-date=March 14, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 15, the mayor of [[Charleston, West Virginia]], declared a state of emergency.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wvpublic.org/post/charleston-wva-declares-state-emergency-part-coronavirus-response|title=Charleston, W.Va. Declares State Of Emergency As Part Of Coronavirus Response|last=Mistich|first=Dave|date=2020-03-15|website=[[West Virginia Public Broadcasting]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\nOn March 16, Governor Justice declared a state of emergency.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.axios.com/coronavirus-west-virginia-only-state-no-case-ac32ce6d-5523-4310-a219-7d1d1dcb6b44.html|title=West Virginia, the only U.S. state with no reported coronavirus cases, declares emergency|last=Falconer|first=Rebecca|website=Axios|language=en|access-date=2020-03-17}}</ref>\n\nOn March 17, Justice ordered restaurant dining rooms, bars, and casinos to close until March 31.<ref name=\"wsaz\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wsaz.com/content/news/Gov-Jim-Justice-confirms-case-of-COVID-19-in-West-Virginia-568875791.html |title=Gov. Jim Justice confirms case of COVID-19 in West Virginia|publisher= WSAZ|date= March 17, 2020|accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nBy March 21, several Mid-Ohio Valley counties had closed their courthouses to the public or limited access.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsandsentinel.com/news/local-news/2020/03/mid-ohio-valley-counties-limiting-access-to-courthouses/|title=Mid-Ohio Valley counties limiting access to courthouses|last=Black|first=Candice|date=2020-03-21|website=[[The Parkersburg News and Sentinel]]|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\nBy March 22, Justice urged West Virginians to [[Stay-at-home order|stay home]] as much as possible.<ref name=\"March 22\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsandsentinel.com/news/local-news/2020/03/justice-not-ready-to-close-west-virginia-as-coronavirus-cases-grow-to-12/|title=Justice not ready to close West Virginia as coronavirus cases grow to 12|last=Adams|first=Steven Allen|date=March 22, 2020|website=[[The Parkersburg News and Sentinel]]|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> Justice was joined by Dr. [[Clay Marsh]], vice president of [[West Virginia University]] and executive dean for Health Sciences. Marsh said that New York is being hit by a tsunami wave of coronavirus cases and if West Virginia can stay home as much as possible the next few weeks, the tsunami wave can become more like a stream for West Virginia.<ref name=\"March 22\"/>\n\n\"We are faced with a pandemic by a virus that we have no immune system that responds to, so we can\u2019t fight it ... If we do these things, we\u2019ll continue to be the leaders. We have demonstrated how we too, as a state pulling together, can protect each other and protect our health care workers. Once this window of opportunity is gone, it won\u2019t matter what we do then.\"<ref name=\"March 22\"/>\n\nOn March 23, Governor Justice ordered non-essential businesses to be closed immediately, and issued a [[stay-at-home order]] effective March 24 at 8 p.m.<ref name=\"WBOY March 23\">{{cite web |title=WATCH LIVE: WV Gov. Justice announces stay at home order during virtual news briefing on COVID-19 |url=https://www.wboy.com/news/health/coronavirus/gov-justice-changes-time-of-monday-address-to-1-p-m/ |publisher=[[WBOY-TV]] |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323183355/https://www.wboy.com/news/health/coronavirus/gov-justice-changes-time-of-monday-address-to-1-p-m/ |archivedate=March 23, 2020 |date=March 23, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Gov. Justice orders shutdown of non-essential businesses in West Virginia; first community-transmitted case has been confirmed |url=https://www.wvnews.com/news/wvnews/gov-justice-orders-shutdown-of-non-essential-businesses-in-west/article_24910f48-6d21-11ea-8518-3fbb944964d3.html |accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=West Virginia's News |date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 25, WV Statewide Day of Prayer, a 45-minute service dedicated to the people affected with Coronavirus disease.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wvnstv.com/video/wv-statewide-day-of-prayer-service/4428831/|title=WV Statewide Day of Prayer Service|website=WVNS|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> It was held by Governor Jim Justice and moderator Dr. Dan Anderson.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://governor.wv.gov/News/press-releases/2020/Pages/Gov.-Justice,-religious-leaders-to-hold-virtual-statewide-Day-of-Prayer-service-tomorrow-at-noon.aspx|title=Gov. Justice, religious leaders to hold virtual statewide Day of Prayer service tomorrow at noon.|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== Federal response ===\nWest Virginia will receive $5.6 million of federal money to fight COVID-19.<ref>[https://www.wvnews.com/news/wvnews/senators-west-virginia-to-receive-nearly-million-for-covid-/article_84856dbd-0431-5122-a3ef-cdcc2d33da0e.html Senators: West Virginia to receive nearly $5.6 million for COVID-19 response] WV News, March 17, 2020</ref>\n\n==Impact on sports==\nOn March 12, the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] cancelled all winter and spring tournaments, most notably the [[NCAA Division I|Division I]] [[2020 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|men]]'s and [[2020 NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament|women]]'s basketball tournaments, affecting colleges and universities statewide.<ref name=ncaa>{{cite web|url=https://www.ncaa.org/about/resources/media-center/news/ncaa-cancels-remaining-winter-and-spring-championships |title=NCAA cancels remaining winter and spring championships|publisher= NCAA|date= March 12, 2020|accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref> On March 16, the [[National Junior College Athletic Association]] also canceled the remainder of the winter seasons as well as the spring seasons.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mlive.com/sports/2020/03/njcaa-cancels-spring-sports-basketball-nationals-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html|title= NJCAA cancels spring sports, basketball nationals amid coronavirus outbreak| publisher= MLive.com|date= March 16, 2020|accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Statistics ==\n<!--Do NOT change the disease totals UNLESS YOU HAVE A SOURCE. PERIOD.-->{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States/West Virginia medical cases chart}}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:right\"\n! colspan=\"3\" |2019 Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) Cases in West Virginia<ref name=\"WVDHHS\"/>\nUpdated April 10, 2020\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |County\n! scope=\"col\" |Confirmed<br>\nCases\n!Deaths\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Barbour County, West Virginia|Barbour County]]\n|4\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Berkeley County, West Virginia|Berkeley County]]\n|89\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Boone County, West Virginia|Boone County]]\n|1\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Braxton County, West Virginia|Braxton County]]\n|1\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Brooke County, West Virginia|Brooke County]]\n|3\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Cabell County, West Virginia|Cabell County]]\n|21\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Fayette County, West Virginia|Fayette County]]\n|3\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Greenbrier  County, West Virginia|Greenbrier  County]]\n|3\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Hampshire County, West Virginia|Hampshire County]]\n|3\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Hancock  County, West Virginia|Hancock  County]]\n|7\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Hardy County, West Virginia|Hardy County]]\n|2\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Harrison County, West Virginia|Harrison County]]\n|28\n|1<ref>{{cite web |title=State records 4th coronaviru