s now over 300, three deaths confirmed |url=https://www.wowktv.com/news/west-virginia/west-virginia-confirmed-covid-19-cases-now-over-300-three-deaths-confirmed/ |website=www.wowktv |publisher=[[WOWK-TV]] |accessdate=April 6, 2020 |date=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" [[Monroe County, West Virginia|Monroe County]]\n|1\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Morgan County, West Virginia|Morgan County]]\n|5\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Nicholas County, West Virginia|Nicholas County]]\n|2\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Ohio County, West Virginia|Ohio County]]\n|21\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Pendleton County, West Virginia|Pendleton County]]\n|1\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Pleasants County, West Virginia|Pleasants County]]\n|1\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Preston County, West Virginia|Preston County]]\n|6\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Putnam County, West Virginia|Putnam County]]\n|10\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Raleigh County, West Virginia|Raleigh County]]\n|5\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Randolph County, West Virginia|Randolph County]]\n|3\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Roane County, West Virginia|Roane County]]\n|2\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Taylor County, West Virginia|Taylor County]]\n|3\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Tucker County, West Virginia|Tucker County]]\n|3\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Tyler County, West Virginia|Tyler County]]\n|3\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Upshur County, West Virginia|Upshur County]]\n|3\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Wayne County, West Virginia|Wayne County]]\n|17\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Wetzel County, West Virginia|Wetzel County]]\n|3\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Wirt County, West Virginia|Wirt County]]\n|2\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Wood County, West Virginia|Wood County]]\n|18\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Wyoming County, West Virginia|Wyoming County]]\n|1\n|0\n|-\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" |Total (statewide)\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" |574\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" |5\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://dhhr.wv.gov/COVID-19 Information] from the West Virginia Department of Health & Human Resources\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{Portal bar|United States|Coronavirus disease 2019|Medicine|Pandemic|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States by state|West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Disasters in West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Health in West Virginia]]\n[[Category:2020 in West Virginia|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in the United States]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Details of ongoing pandemic in West Virginia, United States}}\n{{Current event|2=current pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in West Virginia\n| width           = \n| image           = West Virginia National Guard (49667643407).jpg\n| image_size      = \n| image_upright   = \n| alt             = \n| caption         = Members of the [[West Virginia National Guard]] provide personal protective equipment training on March 16, 2020\n| map1            = COVID-19 In West Virginia County Map.svg\n| legend1         = Density of COVID-19 cases in West Virginia as of April 10\n{{legend|#FFE4A3|1\u201319 cases}}{{legend|#F2A88D|20\u201399 cases}}\n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| map4            = \n| legend4         = \n| map5            = \n| legend5         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[West Virginia]], U.S.\n| first_case      = [[Shepherdstown, West Virginia|Shepherdstown]]\n| arrival_date    = March 17, 2020\n| date            = \n| origin          = \n| confirmed_cases = 574<ref name=\"WVDHHS\">{{cite web |title=Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19) |url=https://dhhr.wv.gov/COVID-19/Pages/default.aspx |publisher=West Virginia Department of Health and Human Services |accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"COVID-19 Daily Update - 4-9-2020 5PM\">{{cite web |title=COVID-19 Daily Update - 4-9-2020 5PM|url=https://dhhr.wv.gov/News/2020/Pages/COVID-19-Daily-Update---4-9-2020---5-PM.aspx |website=dhhr.wv.gov |publisher=[[Government of West Virginia]] |accessdate=April 10, 2020 |date=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n| suspected_cases = \n| severe_cases    = 30<ref name=\"WVDHHS\"/>\n| recovery_cases  = 63<ref name=\"WVDHHS\"/>\n| deaths          = 5<ref name=\"WVDHHS\"/>\n| territories     = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{URL|https://dhhr.wv.gov/COVID-19}}\n}}\n\nThe U.S. state of [[West Virginia]] reported its first case of [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] on March 17, 2020, becoming the last state in the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|United States]] to do so.<ref name=cbspittsburgh>{{cite web|url=https://pittsburgh.cbslocal.com/2020/03/17/coronavirus-in-west-virginia-state-reports-first-positive-covid-19-case/ |title=Coronavirus In West Virginia: State Reports First Positive COVID-19 Case|publisher=CBS Pittsburgh|date=March 17, 2020|accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref> On April 1, 2020 the state reported its first COVID-19 death.<ref name=\"WVDHHS\"/> As of April 10, 2020 the state had reported 574 cases and 5 deaths.<ref name=\"WVDHHS\"/>\n\n==Timeline==\nAs of March 16, the state had tested 84 suspected cases.<ref name=\":22\">{{Cite news|last=Wines|first=Michael|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/14/us/weve-got-a-monster-thats-looming-west-virginia-is-the-last-state-without-a-coronavirus-case.html|title='We've Got a Monster That's Looming': West Virginia Is the Last State Without a Coronavirus Case|date=2020-03-14|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-17|last2=Robertson|first2=Campbell|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> West Virginia announced its first case, in [[Shepherdstown, West Virginia|Shepherdstown]], on March 17, 2020.<ref name=\"wowktv\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wowktv.com/news/west-virginia/covid-19-confirmed-in-west-virginia/|title=COVID-19 confirmed in West Virginia|date=March 17, 2020|website=WOWK 13 News|language=en-US|access-date=March 17, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"wsaz\" /><ref>{{cite news|last=McGuire|first=Colin|date=March 18, 2020|title=First confirmed WV Coronavirus case in Shepherdstown, wife to get tested|url=https://www.journal-news.net/journal-news/first-confirmed-wv-coronavirus-case-in-shepherdstown-wife-to-get/article_3033c813-4675-58a1-b127-d91fc97e1178.html|newspaper=The Journal|location=Martinsburg, West Virginia|access-date=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs of March 18, the second case was announced. Also on that date, 148 West Virginians had been tested for the virus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wvmetronews.com/2020/03/18/second-coronavirus-case-in-west-virginia-confirmed/|title=2nd coronavirus case in West Virginia confirmed|last=WVMetroNews|date=2020-03-19|website=WV MetroNews|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n\nAs of March 20, West Virginia had confirmed 8 cases of COVID-19.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wvmetronews.com/2020/03/20/eighth-coronavirus-case-confirmed-first-case-recognized-in-kanawha-county/|title=Eighth coronavirus case confirmed; first case recognized in Kanawha County|last=WVMetroNews|date=2020-03-20|website=WV MetroNews|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref> On March 22, there were 16 confirmed cases.<ref name=\"WVDHHS\"/>\n\nA March 22 [[The Washington Post|Washington Post]] article described efforts to implement [[social distancing]] in [[Grant County, West Virginia|Grant County]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Frankel |first1=Todd |title=In pro-Trump West Virginia, a fight to convince residents a pandemic is coming |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/2020/03/22/pro-trump-west-virginia-fight-convince-residents-pandemic-is-coming/ |work=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |date=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Government responses==\nOn March 13, Governor [[Jim Justice]] announced all schools across the state would close beginning on March 16, 2020 for an indefinite period of time as a proactive measure.<ref name=wsaz2>{{Cite web |url=https://www.wsaz.com/content/news/WVa-Governor-closing-state-schools-indefinitely-568772291.html |title=W.Va. Gov. Justice closing state schools indefinitely |last=Tierney |first=Brendan |date=March 13, 2020 |website=[[WSAZ-TV]] |language=english |access-date=March 15, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314093424/https://www.wsaz.com/content/news/WVa-Governor-closing-state-schools-indefinitely-568772291.html |archive-date=March 14, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 15, the mayor of [[Charleston, West Virginia]], declared a state of emergency.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wvpublic.org/post/charleston-wva-declares-state-emergency-part-coronavirus-response|title=Charleston, W.Va. Declares State Of Emergency As Part Of Coronavirus Response|last=Mistich|first=Dave|date=2020-03-15|website=[[West Virginia Public Broadcasting]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\nOn March 16, Governor Justice declared a state of emergency.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.axios.com/coronavirus-west-virginia-only-state-no-case-ac32ce6d-5523-4310-a219-7d1d1dcb6b44.html|title=West Virginia, the only U.S. state with no reported coronavirus cases, declares emergency|last=Falconer|first=Rebecca|website=Axios|language=en|access-date=2020-03-17}}</ref>\n\nOn March 17, Justice ordered restaurant dining rooms, bars, and casinos to close until March 31.<ref name=\"wsaz\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wsaz.com/content/news/Gov-Jim-Justice-confirms-case-of-COVID-19-in-West-Virginia-568875791.html |title=Gov. Jim Justice confirms case of COVID-19 in West Virginia|publisher= WSAZ|date= March 17, 2020|accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nBy March 21, several Mid-Ohio Valley counties had closed their courthouses to the public or limited access.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsandsentinel.com/news/local-news/2020/03/mid-ohio-valley-counties-limiting-access-to-courthouses/|title=Mid-Ohio Valley counties limiting access to courthouses|last=Black|first=Candice|date=2020-03-21|website=[[The Parkersburg News and Sentinel]]|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\nBy March 22, Justice urged West Virginians to [[Stay-at-home order|stay home]] as much as possible.<ref name=\"March 22\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsandsentinel.com/news/local-news/2020/03/justice-not-ready-to-close-west-virginia-as-coronavirus-cases-grow-to-12/|title=Justice not ready to close West Virginia as coronavirus cases grow to 12|last=Adams|first=Steven Allen|date=March 22, 2020|website=[[The Parkersburg News and Sentinel]]|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> Justice was joined by Dr. [[Clay Marsh]], vice president of [[West Virginia University]] and executive dean for Health Sciences. Marsh said that New York is being hit by a tsunami wave of coronavirus cases and if West Virginia can stay home as much as possible the next few weeks, the tsunami wave can become more like a stream for West Virginia.<ref name=\"March 22\"/>\n\n\"We are faced with a pandemic by a virus that we have no immune system that responds to, so we can\u2019t fight it ... If we do these things, we\u2019ll continue to be the leaders. We have demonstrated how we too, as a state pulling together, can protect each other and protect our health care workers. Once this window of opportunity is gone, it won\u2019t matter what we do then.\"<ref name=\"March 22\"/>\n\nOn March 23, Governor Justice ordered non-essential businesses to be closed immediately, and issued a [[stay-at-home order]] effective March 24 at 8 p.m.<ref name=\"WBOY March 23\">{{cite web |title=WATCH LIVE: WV Gov. Justice announces stay at home order during virtual news briefing on COVID-19 |url=https://www.wboy.com/news/health/coronavirus/gov-justice-changes-time-of-monday-address-to-1-p-m/ |publisher=[[WBOY-TV]] |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323183355/https://www.wboy.com/news/health/coronavirus/gov-justice-changes-time-of-monday-address-to-1-p-m/ |archivedate=March 23, 2020 |date=March 23, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Gov. Justice orders shutdown of non-essential businesses in West Virginia; first community-transmitted case has been confirmed |url=https://www.wvnews.com/news/wvnews/gov-justice-orders-shutdown-of-non-essential-businesses-in-west/article_24910f48-6d21-11ea-8518-3fbb944964d3.html |accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=West Virginia's News |date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 25, WV Statewide Day of Prayer, a 45-minute service dedicated to the people affected with Coronavirus disease.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wvnstv.com/video/wv-statewide-day-of-prayer-service/4428831/|title=WV Statewide Day of Prayer Service|website=WVNS|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> It was held by Governor Jim Justice and moderator Dr. Dan Anderson.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://governor.wv.gov/News/press-releases/2020/Pages/Gov.-Justice,-religious-leaders-to-hold-virtual-statewide-Day-of-Prayer-service-tomorrow-at-noon.aspx|title=Gov. Justice, religious leaders to hold virtual statewide Day of Prayer service tomorrow at noon.|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== Federal response ===\nWest Virginia will receive $5.6 million of federal money to fight COVID-19.<ref>[https://www.wvnews.com/news/wvnews/senators-west-virginia-to-receive-nearly-million-for-covid-/article_84856dbd-0431-5122-a3ef-cdcc2d33da0e.html Senators: West Virginia to receive nearly $5.6 million for COVID-19 response] WV News, March 17, 2020</ref>\n\n==Impact on sports==\nOn March 12, the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] cancelled all winter and spring tournaments, most notably the [[NCAA Division I|Division I]] [[2020 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|men]]'s and [[2020 NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament|women]]'s basketball tournaments, affecting colleges and universities statewide.<ref name=ncaa>{{cite web|url=https://www.ncaa.org/about/resources/media-center/news/ncaa-cancels-remaining-winter-and-spring-championships |title=NCAA cancels remaining winter and spring championships|publisher= NCAA|date= March 12, 2020|accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref> On March 16, the [[National Junior College Athletic Association]] also canceled the remainder of the winter seasons as well as the spring seasons.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mlive.com/sports/2020/03/njcaa-cancels-spring-sports-basketball-nationals-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html|title= NJCAA cancels spring sports, basketball nationals amid coronavirus outbreak| publisher= MLive.com|date= March 16, 2020|accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Statistics ==\n<!--Do NOT change the disease totals UNLESS YOU HAVE A SOURCE. PERIOD.-->{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States/West Virginia medical cases chart}}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:right\"\n! colspan=\"3\" |2019 Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) Cases in West Virginia<ref name=\"WVDHHS\"/>\nUpdated April 10, 2020\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |County\n! scope=\"col\" |Confirmed<br>\nCases\n!Deaths\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Barbour County, West Virginia|Barbour County]]\n|4\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Berkeley County, West Virginia|Berkeley County]]\n|89\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Boone County, West Virginia|Boone County]]\n|1\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Braxton County, West Vir