ype=NH\n|route=114A\n|length_mi=3.696\n|terminus_a= [[New Hampshire Route 114|NH&nbsp;114]] in [[Goffstown, New Hampshire|Goffstown]]\n|terminus_b= [[Interstate 293 in New Hampshire|I&#8209;293]]&nbsp;/ [[U.S. Route 3 in New Hampshire|US&nbsp;3]]&nbsp;/ [[New Hampshire Route 3A|NH&nbsp;3A]] in [[Manchester, New Hampshire|Manchester]]\n|established=\n|established_ref=\n|notes=none\n}}\n{{routelist row\n|state=NH\n|type=NH\n|route=115A\n|length_mi=4.128\n|terminus_a= [[New Hampshire Route 115|NH&nbsp;115]] in [[Jefferson, New Hampshire|Jefferson]]\n|terminus_b= [[U.S. Route 2 in New Hampshire|US&nbsp;2]] in [[Jefferson, New Hampshire|Jefferson]]\n|established=\n|established_ref=\n|notes=none\n}}\n{{routelist row\n|state=NH\n|type=NH\n|route=115B\n|length_mi=1.5\n|length_ref={{citation needed|date=April 2015}}\n|terminus_a= [[New Hampshire Route 115A|NH&nbsp;115A]] in [[Jefferson, New Hampshire|Jefferson]]\n|terminus_b= [[New Hampshire Route 115|NH&nbsp;115]] in [[Jefferson, New Hampshire|Jefferson]]\n|established=\n|established_ref=\n|notes=none\n}}\n{{routelist row\n|state=NH\n|type=NH\n|route=121A\n|length_mi=15.144\n|terminus_a= [[Massachusetts Route 125|Route&nbsp;125]] in [[Haverhill, Massachusetts|Haverhill, MA]]\n|terminus_b= [[New Hampshire Route 121|NH&nbsp;121]] in [[Chester, New Hampshire|Chester]]\n|established=\n|established_ref=\n|notes=none\n}}\n{{routelist row\n|state=NH\n|type=NH\n|route=123A\n|length_mi=4.216\n|terminus_a=West Road in [[Ashby, Massachusetts|Ashby, MA]]\n|terminus_b= [[New Hampshire Route 123|NH&nbsp;123]]&nbsp;/ [[New Hampshire Route 124|NH&nbsp;124]] in [[New Ipswich, New Hampshire|New Ipswich]]\n|established=\n|established_ref=\n|notes=none\n}}\n{{routelist row\n|state=NH\n|type=NH\n|route=123A\n|length_mi=10.070\n|terminus_a= [[New Hampshire Route 123|NH&nbsp;123]] in [[Alstead, New Hampshire|Alstead]]\n|terminus_b= [[New Hampshire Route 10|NH&nbsp;10]] in [[Marlow, New Hampshire|Marlow]]\n|established=\n|established_ref=\n|notes=none\n}}\n{{routelist row\n|state=NH\n|type=NH\n|route=155A\n|length_mi=3.699\n|terminus_a= [[New Hampshire Route 155|NH&nbsp;155]] in [[Lee, New Hampshire|Lee]]\n|terminus_b= [[New Hampshire Route 155|NH&nbsp;155]] in [[Lee, New Hampshire|Lee]]\n|established=\n|established_ref=\n|notes=none\n}}\n{{routelist row\n|state=NH\n|type=NH\n|route=175A\n|length_mi=0.806\n|terminus_a= [[U.S. Route 3 in New Hampshire|US&nbsp;3]]&nbsp;/ [[New Hampshire Route 25|NH&nbsp;25]] in [[Plymouth, New Hampshire|Plymouth]]\n|terminus_b= [[New Hampshire Route 175|NH&nbsp;175]] in [[Holderness, New Hampshire|Holderness]]\n|established=\n|established_ref=\n|notes=none\n}}\n{{routelist row\n|state=NH\n|type=NH\n|route=202A\n|length_mi=14.639\n|terminus_a= [[U.S. Route 202 in New Hampshire|US&nbsp;202]]&nbsp;/ [[New Hampshire Route 9|NH&nbsp;9]] in [[Northwood, New Hampshire|Northwood]]\n|terminus_b= [[New Hampshire Route 108|NH&nbsp;108]]&nbsp;/ [[New Hampshire Route 125|NH&nbsp;125]] in [[Rochester, New Hampshire|Rochester]]\n|established=\n|established_ref=\n|notes=Loop of [[U.S. Route 202]]\n}}\n{{routelist bottom|keys=former}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.roadgeek.org/nhroads/ Granite State Roads]\n* [http://mdo20.0catch.com/route/nh/nhsign.html Road Signs of New Hampshire]\n\n[[Category:State highways in New Hampshire| ]]\n[[Category:Lists of roads in New Hampshire|State routes]]\n", "name_user": "Dmoore5556", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePrimary routes:refine a page link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_state_routes_in_New_Hampshire"}
{"title_page": "Circus Flaminius", "text_new": "{{coord|41.8927578|12.4774218|scale:2000_region:IT_type:landmark|format=dms|display=title}}\n[[File:Circus Flaminius by Giacomo Lauro.jpg|thumb|300px|Engraving of the Circus Flaminius by [[Giacomo Lauro]] in 1641.]]\nThe '''Circus Flaminius''' was a large, circular area in [[ancient Rome]], located in the southern end of the [[Campus Martius]] near the [[Tiber River]].<ref>Pier Luigi Tucci, 'Nuove ricerche sulla topografia dell\u2019area del circo Flaminio\u2019, ''Studi Romani'' 41 (1993) 229-242</ref> It contained a small race-track used for obscure games, and various other buildings and monuments. It was \"built\", or sectioned off, by [[Gaius Flaminius]] in 221 BC.<ref name=\"Humphrey1986\">{{cite book|author=John H. Humphrey|title=Roman Circuses: Arenas for Chariot Racing|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=couetXBQO9AC&pg=PA543|date=1 January 1986|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-04921-5|pages=543\u2013}}</ref> After [[Augustus]] divided the city into [[14 regions of Augustan Rome|14 administrative regions]], the Circus Flaminius gave its name to Region IX, which encompassed the Circus and all of the Campus Martius west of the [[Via Lata (Rome)|Via Lata]].<ref>{{cite book| title=Atlas of Ancient Rome| author=Andrea Carandini| publisher=Princeton University Press| year=2017| p=493-495}}</ref>\n\n==Topography and structures==\nIn its early existence, the Circus was a loop, approximately 500 meters in length stretching across the Flaminian Fields (''Prata Flaminia''). The Fields were already a hallowed site for games by the time the Circus was built in 220 BC. The ''[[Taurian Games|ludi Taurei]]'' were hosted annually in the Fields since they were inaugurated by Rome's last king [[Lucius Tarquinius Superbus]] (d. 495 BC).<ref>{{cite book| title=Atlas of Ancient Rome| author=Andrea Carandini| publisher=Princeton University Press| year=2017| p=498-500}}</ref>\n\nDuring the 2nd century BC, this broad space was encroached upon by buildings and monuments.  The circus had no permanent seating, nor were there any permanent structures to mark the perimeter of the race track. By the early 3rd century AD, the only open space that remained was a small piazza in the center, no more than 300 meters long, where the ''[[ludi]]'' (public games) had always been held.\n\nThere were many structures in the vicinity of the circus (\u201cin circo Flaminio\u201d). The [[Temple of Pietas]] lay on the edge of the [[Forum Holitorium]] to the southeast. The Temple of Mars was situated in the northwest. It is estimated that by 220 BC there were six temples, including one to [[Apollo]], in the Flaminian Fields. A theatre dedicated to Apollo was also set up in 179 BC, close to the temple of Apollo, and later rebuilt under the dictatorship of [[Caesar]]. The rebuilding of the theatre necessitated shortening the Circus itself, and required that several temples be destroyed.<ref>{{cite book| title=Atlas of Ancient Rome| author=Andrea Carandini| publisher=Princeton University Press| year=2017| p=507}}</ref> \n\nThe temple of Apollo \"''in circo''\" acquired special significance under Augustus, as a popular legend developed that he had been sired by the god while his mother [[Atia (mother of Augustus)|Atia]] was visiting the temple.<ref>{{cite book| title=Atlas of Ancient Rome| author=Andrea Carandini| publisher=Princeton University Press| year=2017| p=506}}</ref> Augustus undertook myriad new constructions around the Circus, and probably had it paved for the first time. Most notably Augustus demolished the small theater dedicated to Apollo, as well as the temples of Diana and Pietas, to build the [[Theatre of Marcellus]] on the eastern side of the Circus.<ref name=\"Flaminius\">{{cite book| title=Atlas of Ancient Rome| author=Andrea Carandini| publisher=Princeton University Press| year=2017| p=510-511}}</ref> Augustus also built the [[Porticus Octaviae]], which hemmed in the Circus on its northeastern side.<ref>{{cite book| url=http://archive1.village.virginia.edu/spw4s/RomanForum/GoogleEarth/AK_GE/AK_HTML/GF-008.html|title=Rome Alive: A Source Guide to the Ancient City, Vol. 1| author=Peter Aicher| publisher=Bolchazy-Carducci| year=2004}}</ref> Augustus' relation [[Lucius Marcius Philippus (consul 38 BC)|Lucius Marcius Phillipus]] restored the [[Temple of Hercules Musarum]] with a surrounding portico that could be accessed from the Circus.<ref name=\"Flaminius\"/>\n\nIn AD 15, statues to the deified Augustus were erected, dedicated by [[Gaius Norbanus Flaccus (consul 15)|C. Norbanus Flaccus]]. In the early Principate two monumental arches were added at the north and south ends of the Circus, the northern one dedicated to [[Germanicus]] in the year of his death (19 AD), and the southern one to the stepson of Augustus, [[Nero Claudius Drusus|Drusus]].<ref>{{cite book| title=Atlas of Ancient Rome| author=Andrea Carandini| publisher=Princeton University Press| year=2017| p=515}}</ref> \n\nA fragment of the [[Severan marble plan]] preserves a mention of the Circus Flaminius.\n\n==Use==\nThe Circus Flaminius was never meant to rival the much larger [[Circus Maximus]], and, unlike the Circus Maximus, it was not just an entertainment venue. It almost certainly lacked a track designed for [[chariot racing]].<ref>[[T.P. Wiseman]], ''Remus: A Roman Myth'' (Cambridge University Press, 1995), p. 211</ref> The only ''ludi'' held there were the [[Taurian Games]], which featured horseback racing around turning posts ''(metae)''.<ref>[[Varro]], ''De lingua latina'' 5.154; also recorded by the ''[[Fasti Ostienses]]''.</ref> The obscure Taurian Games were held to [[propitiation|propitiate]] the gods of the underworld ''([[Di Inferi|di inferi]])'', and seem to have been symbolically grounded in the site itself, as they were never moved to a different circus. Equestrian events were also associated with underworld deities in other rituals and festivals in the Campus Martius. [[Strabo]] makes no mention of equestrian activities taking place in the Circus Flaminius. [[Valerius Maximus]], who is likely to be in error, is the only ancient source that claims the ''Ludi Plebeii'' ([[Plebeian Games]]) were held there. In 2 BC, the circus was flooded for the slaughter of 36 crocodiles to commemorate the building of the [[Forum of Augustus]].<ref> Cassius Dio ''Roman History'' 55.10</ref>\n\nThe Circus also hosted ceremonies related to the [[Roman triumph]], as the Flaminian Fields traditionally figured along the triumphal route towards Capitoline Hill. In 63 BC [[Lucullus|Lucius Licinius Lucullus]] celebrated his triumph in the [[Third Mithridatic War]] and exhibited his spoils in the Circus, including a solid gold statue of [[Mithridates VI of Pontus|Mithridates]].<ref>{{cite book| title=Atlas of Ancient Rome| author=Andrea Carandini| publisher=Princeton University Press| year=2017| p=506}}</ref> Augustus did the same when he exhibited the captured insignia of the enemy armies from his campaigns in [[Dalmatia (Roman province)|Dalmatia]] in the northern part of the Circus.\n\nAccording to [[Plutarch]], the Dictator [[Sulla]] massacred 6,000 prisoners in the Circus Flaminius after the [[Battle of the Colline Gate (82 BC)|Battle of the Colline Gate]] in 82 BC. Prisoners of war from the nearby town of [[Antemnae]] were rounded up in the Circus and slaughtered while the Senate met in the adjacent [[Temple of Bellona, Rome|Temple of Bellona]]; the screams which could be heard from the Temple were a way of intimidating the Senators.<ref>Plutarch, ''Parallel Lives''; XXX.II</ref>\n\nThe Circus Flaminius was also used as a market. [[Roman assemblies|Assemblies]] were often held within it. In 9 BC, it was the venue when [[Augustus]] delivered the ''Laudatio'' of Drusus.\n\n==Later history==\nThe buildings remained in use until the end of the fourth century, when the area was finally abandoned. Throughout the middle ages, the ruins of the Circus were prominent in the Campus Martius. The structure was referred to in the year 1192 in a [[Papal Bull|Bull]] of [[Pope Celestine III]], who called it the \"Golden Castle\" (''Castellum Aureum'').<ref name=\"Lanciani\"/> At this point the circus could still be entered at one end through a gateway in the [[Carceres]]; the most conspicuous parts were the arcades which ran lengthwise on both sides. The ''Via delle Botteghe Oscure'' (\"Street of Dark Shops\"), as the thoroughfare continues to be known, was first given the name in the middle ages because it ran along the southern arcades of the Circus, which sheltered the workshops of artisans like rope-makers and the lime-burners who quarried stone from the ruins.<ref name=\"Lanciani\">{{cite book| title=The Ruins & Excavations of Ancient Rome| author=Rodolfo Lanciani| publisher=Houghton Mifflin & Co.| year=1897| p=451-452}}</ref>\n\nIn 1555 the [[Roman Ghetto|Jewish Ghetto]] in Rome was established by [[Pope Paul IV]] in an area which encompassed much of the former Circus Flaminius. The [[Great Synagogue of Rome]] stands roughly where the southern end of the arena was located.<ref>{{cite book| url=http://archive1.village.virginia.edu/spw4s/RomanForum/GoogleEarth/AK_GE/AK_HTML/GF-008.html|title=Rome Alive: A Source Guide to the Ancient City, Vol. 1| author=Peter Aicher| publisher=Bolchazy-Carducci| year=2004}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite book\n  | last = Platner\n  | first = Samuel\n  | authorlink = Samuel Platner\n  | title = A Topographical Dictionary of Ancient Rome\n  | publisher = Oxford University Press\n  | year = 1929 }}\n*{{cite encyclopedia\n  | title = Civilization of the ancient Mediterranean: Greece and Rome\n  | volume = II\n  | publisher = Scribner's\n  | year = 1998 }}\n*{{cite book\n  | last = Humphrey\n  | first = John\n  | authorlink = \n  | title = Roman Circuses: Arenas for Chariot Racing\n  | publisher = Butler & Tanner Ltd.\n  | year = 1986\n  | pages = 540\u2013545\n  | isbn = 0-520-04921-7 }}\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures completed in the 3rd century BC]]\n[[Category:Ancient Roman circuses in Rome]]\n[[Category:Topography of the ancient city of Rome]]\n", "text_old": "{{coord|41.8927578|12.4774218|scale:2000_region:IT_type:landmark|format=dms|display=title}}\n[[File:Circus Flaminius by Giacomo Lauro.jpg|thumb|300px|Engraving of the Circus Flaminius by [[Giacomo Lauro]] in 1641.]]\nThe '''Circus Flaminius''' was a large, circular area in [[ancient Rome]], located in the southern end of the [[Campus Martius]] near the [[Tiber River]].<ref>Pier Luigi Tucci, 'Nuove ricerche sulla topografia dell\u2019area del circo Flaminio\u2019, ''Studi Romani'' 41 (1993) 229-242</ref> It contained a small race-track used for obscure games, and various other buildings and monuments. It was \"built\", or sectioned off, by [[Gaius Flaminius]] in 221 BC.<ref name=\"Humphrey1986\">{{cite book|author=John H. Humphrey|title=Roman Circuses: Arenas for Chariot Racing|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=couetXBQO9AC&pg=PA543|date=1 January 1986|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-04921-5|pages=543\u2013}}</ref> After [[Augustus]] divided the city into [[14 regions of Augustan Rome|14 administrative regions]], the Circus Flaminius gave its name to Region IX, which encompassed the Circus and all of the Campus Martius west of the [[Via Lata (Rome)|Via Lata]].<ref>{{cite book| title=Atlas of Ancient Rome| author=Andrea Carandini| publisher=Princeton University Press| year=2017| p=493-495}}</ref>\n\n==Topography and structures==\nIn its early existence, the Circus was a loop, approximately 500 meters in length stretching across the Flaminian Fields (''Prata Flaminia''). The Fields were already a hallowed site for games by the time the Circus was built in 220 BC. The ''[[Taurian Games|ludi Taurei]]'' were hosted annually in the Fields since they were inaugurated by Rome's last king [[Lucius Tarquinius Superbus]] (d. 495 BC).<ref>{{cite book| title=Atlas of Ancient Rome| author=Andrea Carandini| publisher=Princeton University Press| year=2017| p=498-500}}</ref>\n\nDuring the 2nd century BC, this broad space was encroached upon by buildings and monuments.  The circus had no permanent seating, nor were there any permanent structures to mark the perimeter of the race track. By the early 3rd century AD, the only open space that remained was a small piazza in the center, no more than 300 meters long, where the ''[[ludi]]'' (public games) had always been held.\n\nThere were many structures in the vicinity of the circus (\u201cin circo Flaminio\u201d). The [[Temple of Pietas]] lay on the edge of the [[Forum Holitorium]] to the southeast. The Temple of Mars was situated in the northwest. It is estimated that by 220 BC there were six temples, including one to [[Apollo]], in the Flaminian Fields. A theatre dedicated to Apollo was also set up in 179 BC, close to the temple of Apollo, and later rebuilt under the dictatorship of [[Caesar]]. The rebuilding of the theatre necessitated shortening the Circus itself, and required that several temples be destroyed.<ref>{{cite book| title=Atlas of Ancient Rome| author=Andrea Carandini| publisher=Princeton University Press| year=2017| p=507}}</ref> \n\nThe temple of Apollo \"''in circo''\" acquired special significance under Augustus, as a popular legend developed that he had been sired by the god while his mother [[Atia (mother of Augustus)|Atia]] was visiting the temple.<ref>{{cite book| title=Atlas of Ancient Rome| author=Andrea Carandini| publisher=Princeton University Press| year=2017| p=506}}</ref> Augustus undertook myriad new constructions around the Circus, and probably had it paved for the first time. Most notably Augustus demolished the small theater dedicated to Apollo, as well as the temples of Diana and Pietas, to build the [[Theatre of Marcellus]] on the eastern side of the Circus.<ref name=\"Flaminius\">{{cite book| title=Atlas of Ancient Rome| author=Andrea Carandini| publisher=Princeton University Press| year=2017| p=510-511}}</ref> Augustus also built the [[Porticus Octaviae]], which hemmed in the Circus on its northeastern side.<ref>{{cite book| url=http://archive1.village.virginia.edu/spw4s/RomanForum/GoogleEarth/AK_GE/AK_HTML/GF-008.html|title=Rome Alive: A Source Guide to the Ancient City, Vol. 1| author=Peter Aicher| publisher=Bolchazy-Carducci| year=2004}}</ref> Augustus' relation [[Lucius Marcius Philippus (consul 38 BC)|Lucius Marcius Phillipus]] restored the [[Temple of Hercules Musarum]] with a surrounding portico that could be accessed from the Circus.<ref name=\"Flaminius\"/>\n\nIn AD 15, statues to the deified Augustus were erected, dedicated by [[Gaius Norbanus Flaccus (consul 15)|C. Norbanus Flaccus]]. In the early Principate two monumental arches were added at the north and south ends of the Circus, the northern one dedicated to [[Germanicus]] in the year of his death (19 AD), and the southern one to Tiberius' brother [[Nero Claudius Drusus|Drusus]].<ref>{{cite book| title=Atlas of Ancient Rome| author=Andrea Carandini| publisher=Princeton University Press| year=2017| p=515}}</ref> \n\nA fragment of the [[Severan marble plan]] preserves a mention of the Circus Flaminius.\n\n==Use==\nThe Circus Flaminius was never meant to rival the much larger [[Circus Maximus]], and, unlike the Circus Maximus, it was not just an entertainment venue. It almost certainly lacked a track designed for [[chariot racing]].<ref>[[T.P. Wiseman]], ''Remus: A Roman Myth'' (Cambridge University Press, 1995), p. 211</ref> The only ''ludi'' held there were the [[Taurian Games]], which featured horseback racing around turning posts ''(metae)''.<ref>[[Varro]], ''De lingua latina'' 5.154; also recorded by the ''[[Fasti Ostienses]]''.</ref> The obscure Taurian Games were held to [[propitiation|propitiate]] the gods of the underworld ''([[Di Inferi|di inferi]])'', and seem to have been symbolically grounded in the site itself, as they were never moved to a different circus. Equestrian events were also associated with underworld deities in other rituals and festivals in the Campus Martius. [[Strabo]] makes no mention of equestrian activities taking place in the Circus Flaminius. [[Valerius Maximus]], who is likely to be in error, is the only ancient source that claims the ''Ludi Plebeii'' ([[Plebeian Games]]) were held there. In 2 BC, the circus was flooded for the slaughter of 36 crocodiles to commemorate the building of the [[Forum of Augustus]].<ref> Cassius Dio ''Roman History'' 55.10</ref>\n\nThe Circus also hosted ceremonies related to the [[Roman triumph]], as the Flaminian Fields traditionally figured along the triumphal route towards Capitoline Hill. In 63 BC [[Lucullus|Lucius Licinius Lucullus]] celebrated his triumph in the [[Third Mithridatic War]] and exhibited his spoils in the Circus, including a solid gold statue of [[Mithridates VI of Pontus|Mithridates]].<ref>{{cite book| title=Atlas of Ancient Rome| author=Andrea Carandini| publisher=Princeton University Press| year=2017| p=506}}</ref> Augustus did the same when he exhibited the captured insignia of the enemy armies from his campaigns in [[Dalmatia (Roman province)|Dalmatia]] in the northern part of the Circus.\n\nAccording to [[Plutarch]], the Dictator [[Sulla]] massacred 6,000 prisoners in the Circus Flaminius after the [[Battle of the Colline Gate (82 BC)|Battle of the Colline Gate]] in 82 BC. Prisoners of war from the nearby town of [[Antemnae]] were rounded up in the Circus and slaughtered while the Senate met in the adjacent [[Temple of Bellona, Rome|Temple of Bellona]]; the screams which could be heard from the Temple were a way of intimidating the Senators.<ref>Plutarch, ''Parallel Lives''; XXX.II</ref>\n\nThe Circus Flaminius was also used as a market. [[Roman assemblies|Assemblies]] were often held within it. In 9 BC, it was the venue when [[Augustus]] delivered the ''Laudatio'' of Drusus.\n\n==Later history==\nThe buildings remained in use until the end of the fourth century, when the area was finally abandoned. Throughout the middle ages, the ruins of the Circus were prominent in the Campus Martius. The structure was referred to in the year 1192 in a [[Papal Bull|Bull]] of [[Pope Celestine III]], who called it the \"Golden Castle\" (''Castellum Aureum'').<ref name=\"Lanciani\"/> At this point the circus could still be entered at one end through a gateway in the [[Carceres]]; the most conspicuous parts were the arcades which ran lengthwise on both sides. The ''Via delle Botteghe Oscure'' (\"Street of Dark Shops\"), as the thoroughfare continues to be known, was first given the name in the middle ages because it ran along the southern arcades of the Circus, which sheltered the workshops of artisans like rope-makers and the lime-burners who quarried stone from the ruins.<ref name=\"Lanciani\">{{cite book| title=The Ruins & Excavations of Ancient Rome| author=Rodolfo Lanciani| publisher=Houghton Mifflin & Co.| year=1897| p=451-452}}</ref>\n\nIn 1555 the [[Roman Ghetto|Jewish Ghetto]] in Rome was established by [[Pope Paul IV]] in an area which encompassed much of the former Circus Flaminius. The [[Great Synagogue of Rome]] stands roughly where the southern end of the arena was located.<ref>{{cite book| url=http://archive1.village.virginia.edu/spw4s/RomanForum/GoogleEarth/AK_GE/AK_HTML/GF-008.html|title=Rome Alive: A Source Guide to the Ancient City, Vol. 1| author=Peter Aicher| publisher=Bolchazy-Carducci| year=2004}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite book\n  | last = Platner\n  | first = Samuel\n  | authorlink = Samuel Platner\n  | title = A Topographical Dictionary of Ancient Rome\n  | publisher = Oxford University Press\n  | year = 1929 }}\n*{{cite encyclopedia\n  | title = Civilization of the ancient Mediterranean: Greece and Rome\n  | volume = II\n  | publisher = Scribner's\n  | year = 1998 }}\n*{{cite book\n  | last = Humphrey\n  | first = John\n  | authorlink = \n  | title = Roman Circuses: Arenas for Chariot Racing\n  | publisher = Butler & Tanner Ltd.\n  | year = 1986\n  | pages = 540\u2013545\n  | isbn = 0-520-04921-7 }}\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures completed in the 3rd century BC]]\n[[Category:Ancient Roman circuses in Rome]]\n[[Category:Topography of the ancient city of Rome]]\n", "name_user": "Volubilis90", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTopography and structures", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Circus_Flaminius"}
